"Walters R.J., Hassall M., Telfer M.G., Hewitt G.M., Palutikof J.P.","Modelling dispersal of a temperate insect in a changing climate",2006,"Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences","273","1597",,"2017","2023",,,10.1098/rspb.2006.3542,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33747140111&partnerID=40&md5=3b0f0dbc007138dee6ed09b3ee6dfb2a","School of Environmental Sciences, University of East Anglia, Norwich NR4 7TJ, United Kingdom; School of Biological Sciences, University of East Anglia, Norwich NR4 7TJ, United Kingdom; Climatic Research Unit, University of East Anglia, Norwich NR4 7TJ, United Kingdom; Biological Records Centre, CEH, Monks Wood, Huntingdon, Cambridgeshire PE28 2LS, United Kingdom; Department of Zoology, Stockholm University, 106 91 Stockholm, Sweden; Royal Society for the Protection of Birds, The Lodge, Sandy, Bedfordshire SG19 2DL, United Kingdom; IPCC WGII Technical Support Unit (TSU), Hadley Centre for Climate Prediction and Research, Met Office, FitzRoy Road, Exeter EX1 3PB, United Kingdom","Walters, R.J., School of Environmental Sciences, University of East Anglia, Norwich NR4 7TJ, United Kingdom, Department of Zoology, Stockholm University, 106 91 Stockholm, Sweden; Hassall, M., School of Environmental Sciences, University of East Anglia, Norwich NR4 7TJ, United Kingdom; Telfer, M.G., Biological Records Centre, CEH, Monks Wood, Huntingdon, Cambridgeshire PE28 2LS, United Kingdom, Royal Society for the Protection of Birds, The Lodge, Sandy, Bedfordshire SG19 2DL, United Kingdom; Hewitt, G.M., School of Biological Sciences, University of East Anglia, Norwich NR4 7TJ, United Kingdom; Palutikof, J.P., Climatic Research Unit, University of East Anglia, Norwich NR4 7TJ, United Kingdom, IPCC WGII Technical Support Unit (TSU), Hadley Centre for Climate Prediction and Research, Met Office, FitzRoy Road, Exeter EX1 3PB, United Kingdom","We construct a novel individual-based random-walk model to assess how predicted global climate change might affect the dispersal rates of a temperate insect. Using a novel approach we obtained accurate field measurements of daily movements for individuals over time to parameterize our model. Males were found to move significantly further on average than females. Significant variation in movement was evident among individuals; the most dispersive individuals moved up to five (females) and seven (males) times as far on average as the least dispersive individuals. Mean relative daily movement of both males and females were exponentially related to maximum daily temperature recorded within the grass sward. Variability, both within and among individuals, in relative daily movement was incorporated into the model using gamma probability distributions. Resultant dispersal functions for seasonal movement are predicted to be highly leptokurtic, which agrees well with observations from the field. Predictions of the model suggest that for populations at the polewards edge of the current range an increase of 3-5 °C in daily maximum temperature may increase the proportion of long-distance dispersere (those characterized as comprising the top 0.1% of furthest dispersing individuals under local conditions experienced during the 1963-1990 period) by up to 70%. © 2006 The Royal Society.","Dispersal curve; Gene-flow; Long-distance dispersal; Orthoptera; Range expansion; Weather","climate change; dispersal; insect; modeling; random walk method; temperate environment; article; biological model; climate change; controlled study; female; insect; male; nonhuman; priority journal; probability; seasonal variation; species distribution; species diversity; temperature measurement; Animals; Climate; Female; Grasshoppers; Greenhouse Effect; Homing Behavior; Male; Models, Biological; Temperature; Insecta",,,,,,"Aikman, D., Hewitt, G.M., An experimental investigation of the rate and form of dispersal in grasshoppers (1972) J. Appl Ecol., 9, pp. 809-817; Bailey, R.I., Lineham, M.E., Thomas, C.D., Butlin, R.K., Measuring dispersal and detecting departures from a random walk model in a grasshopper hybrid zone (2003) Ecol. Entomol, 28, pp. 129-138. , doi:10.1046/j.1365-2311.2003.00504.x; Berggren, A., Birath, B., Kindvall, O., Effect of corridors and habitat edges on dispersal behavior, movement rates and movement angles in Roesel's bush-cricket (Metrioptera roeselli) (2002) Cons. Biol., 16, pp. 1562-1569; Chapman, J.W., Reynolds, D.R., Smith, A.D., Smith, E.T., Woiwod, I.P., An aerial netting study of insects migrating at high altitude over England (2004) Bull. Entomol. Res., 94, pp. 123-136. , doi:10.1079/BER2004287; Clark, D.P., An analysis of dispersal and movement in Pharulacridium vittatus (Sjost) (Acrididae) (1962) Aust. J. Zool., 10, pp. 382-399. , doi:10.1071/ZO9620382; Clark, J.S., Why trees migrate so fast: Confronting theory with dispersal biology and the paleorecord (1998) Am. Nat., 152, pp. 204-224. , doi:10.1086/286162; Clobert, J., Danchin, E., Dhondt, A.A., Nichols, J.D., (2001) Dispersal, p. 452. , Oxford, UK: Oxford University Press; Conradt, L., Roper, T.J., Thomas, C.D., Dispersal behaviour of individuals in metapopulations of two British butterflies (2001) Oikos, 95, pp. 416-424. , doi:10.1034/j.1600-0706.2001.950306.x; Doerr, E.D., Doerr, V.A.J., Dispersal range analysis: Quantifying individual variation in dispersal behaviour (2005) Oecologia, 142, pp. 1-10. , doi:10.1007/s00442-004-1707-z; Fischer, S.K., Poschlod, P., Beinlich, B., Experimental studies on the dispersal of plants and animals on sheep in calcareous grasslands (1996) J. Appl. Ecol., 33, pp. 1206-1222; Fraser, D.F., Gilliam, J.F., Daley, M.J., Le, A.N., Skalski, G.T., Explaining leptokurtic movement distributions: Intrapopulation variation in boldness and exploration (2001) Am. Nat., 158, pp. 124-135. , doi:10.1086/321307; Hanski, I., Breuker, C.J., Schöps, K., Setchfield, R., Nieminen, M., Population history and life history influence the migration rate of female